The signature files live in this module under
src/test/resources/ee/jakarta/tck/faces/signaturetest/ and are generated using
the sigtest-maven-plugin (version 2.1).

Generation and testing are split across two modules:

  - faces-signature-generator : used by TCK maintainers to (re)generate the
    signature file from a known-good API artefact. Not needed to run the tests.
  - faces-signature-test      : runs the signature test against a Faces
    implementation (this module).



For TCK developers (to regenerate the signature file) :-

  Note: the old 'mvn install -Precord-signature' profile no longer exists. As of
  the 4.1.0 update it was replaced by the dedicated faces-signature-generator
  module, which runs the sigtest-maven-plugin 'generate' goal.

  1. Make sure the API artefact you want to record is installed in the local
     Maven repository, e.g. from the api module:

       cd <faces>/api && mvn install

     The generator records the jakarta.faces-api version referenced by
     ${jakarta.faces-api.version} (the current snapshot by default).

  2. Run the generator (requires Java 17), from the tck/ directory:

       mvn -pl faces-signature-generator clean package

     This unpacks the API and its dependencies and writes
     faces-signature-generator/target/jakarta.faces.sig_${project.version}
     (e.g. jakarta.faces.sig_5.0.0-SNAPSHOT).

  3. Copy the generated file into this module's resources, renamed to match the
     version in sig-test.map (which strips the -SNAPSHOT suffix):

       cp faces-signature-generator/target/jakarta.faces.sig_5.0.0-SNAPSHOT \
          faces-signature-test/src/test/resources/ee/jakarta/tck/faces/signaturetest/jakarta.faces.sig_5.0.0

     The committed baseline omits private members (hfds/hcls) of JDK
     super-classes such as java.lang.Throwable; some JDK versions emit these
     during generation. The test ignores those classes (see the
     -IgnoreJDKClass list in SigTestDriver), so such lines can be dropped to
     keep the baseline minimal and JDK-independent.

  4. The package list (sig-test-pkg-list.txt) and the api-to-version mapping
     (sig-test.map) must stay in sync with the <packages> recorded by the
     generator and the version under test.



For TCK users (to run the signature test as a JUnit test) :-

  1. Set the below system properties correctly :

    jimage.dir                       // location the JDK modules are extracted to
    optional.tech.packages.to.ignore // optional packages to ignore during the test
    signature.sigTestClasspath       // implementation jar under test plus its dependencies

    For eg (see this module's pom.xml for the authoritative values):

    <jimage.dir>${project.build.directory}/jdk-bundle</jimage.dir>
    <optional.tech.packages.to.ignore>jakarta.xml.bind</optional.tech.packages.to.ignore>
    <signature.sigTestClasspath>${project.build.directory}/jakarta.faces-vendor-api.jar:${project.build.directory}/jakarta.el-api.jar:${project.build.directory}/jakarta.enterprise.cdi-api.jar:${project.build.directory}/jakarta.servlet-api.jar:${project.build.directory}/jakarta.websocket-client-api.jar:${project.build.directory}/jakarta.websocket-api.jar:${project.build.directory}/jakarta.inject-api.jar:${project.build.directory}/jdk-bundle/java.base:${project.build.directory}/jdk-bundle/java.rmi:${project.build.directory}/jdk-bundle/java.sql:${project.build.directory}/jdk-bundle/java.naming</signature.sigTestClasspath>

  2. The signature test can be run using the below command within the
     faces-signature-test/ directory.

  mvn verify
